"Nevo E.","Evolution under environmental stress at macro- and microscales",2011,"Genome Biology and Evolution","3","1",,"1039","1052",,,10.1093/gbe/evr052,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-84856133461&partnerID=40&md5=d34de21b33261062e15a0f7536ac919a","Institute of Evolution, University of Haifa, Haifa, Israel","Nevo, E., Institute of Evolution, University of Haifa, Haifa, Israel","Environmental stress has played a major role in the evolution of living organisms (Hoffman AA, Parsons PA. 1991. Evolutionary genetics and environmental stress. Oxford: Oxford University Press; Parsons PA. 2005. Environments and evolution: interactions between stress, resource inadequacy, and energetic efficiency. Biol Rev Camb Philos Soc. 80:589-610). This is reflected by the massive and background extinctions in evolutionary time (Nevo E. 1995a. Evolution and extinction. Encyclopedia of Environmental Biology. New York: Academic Press, Inc. 1:717-745). The interaction between organism and environment is central in evolution. Extinction ensues when organisms fail to change and adapt to the constantly altering abiotic and biotic stressful environmental changes as documented in the fossil record. Extreme environmental stress causes extinction but also leads to evolutionary change and the origination of new species adapted to new environments. I will discuss a few of these global, regional, and local stresses based primarily on my own research programs. These examples will include the 1) global regional and local experiment of subterranean mammals; 2) regional experiment of fungal life in the Dead Sea; 3) evolution of wild cereals; 4) ""Evolution Canyon""; 5) human brain evolution, and 6) global warming. © The Author(s) 2010.","""Evolution Canyon""; Dead Sea; Global warming; Stress; Subterranean mammals","Mammalia; DNA; adaptation; animal; article; cereal; climate; ecosystem; environment; evolution; fossil; genetic marker; genetics; human; isolation and purification; mammal; physiological stress; population genetics; sequence analysis; Adaptation, Physiological; Animals; Biological Evolution; Cereals; Climate; DNA; Ecosystem; Environment; Fossils; Genetic Markers; Genetics, Population; Humans; Mammals; Sequence Analysis, RNA; Stress, Physiological",,"DNA, 9007-49-2; DNA, 9007-49-2; Genetic Markers",,,,"Arieli, R., Arieli, M., Heth, G., Nevo, E., Adaptive respiratory variation in 4 chromosomal species of mole rats (1984) Experientia, 40 (5), pp. 512-514; Arieli, R., Heth, G., Nevo, E., Hoch, D., Hematocrit and hemoglobin concentration in four chromosomal species and some isolated populations of actively speciating subterranean mole rats in Israel (1986) Experientia, 42 (4), pp. 441-443; Arieli, R., Heth, G., Nevo, E., Adaptive heart and breathing frequencies in 4 ecologically differentiating chromosomal species of mole rats in Israel (1986) Experientia, 42 (2), pp. 131-133; Arieli, R., Nevo, E., Hypoxic survival differs between two mole rat species (Spalax ehrenbergi) of humid and arid habitats (1991) Comp Biochem Physiol A Comp Physiol., 3, pp. 543-545; Ashur-Fabian, O., Avivi, A., Trakhtenbrot, L., Adamsky, K., Cohen, M., Kajakaro, G., Joel, A., Rechavi, G., Evolution of p53 in hypoxia-stressed Spalax mimics human tumor mutation (2004) Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America, 101 (33), pp. 12236-12241. , DOI 10.1073/pnas.0404998101; Atwell, S., (2010) Genome-wide Association Study of 107 Phenotypes; Avivi, A., Ashur-Fabian, O., Amariglio, N., Nevo, E., Rechavi, G., P53 - A key player in tumoral and evolutionary adaptation. A lesson from the Israeli blind subterranean mole rat (2005) Cell Cycle, 4 (3), pp. e48-e52; Avivi, A., Brodsky, L., Nevo, E., Band, M.R., Differential expression profiling of the blind subterranean mole rat Spalax ehrenbergi superspecies: Bioprospecting for hypoxia tolerance (2006) Physiological Genomics, 27 (1), pp. 54-64. , http://physiolgenomics.physiology.org/cgi/reprint